Introduction
\layout Standard

This report outlines the management issues and policies which were raised
 during the execution of the CS3 System Design group practical.
 It explains how the project was planned, and how the tasks were allocated
 to the members of the group.
 It also concludes the project with an evaluation of the relative contribution
 and effort made by each member of the group.
\layout Section

Allocation of Tasks
\layout Subsection

Initial Allocation
\layout Standard

From the start of the project, it was decided that the tasks involved in
 carrying out the exercise should be divided into three broad categories;
 these were defined as software, hardware and documentation.
 The software category covered all software tasks, from writing the low-level
 routines, up to the front-end system and graphical user interface (GUI).
 The hardware category was defined as the design and construction of the
 prototype hardware and auxilliary components.
 It was recognised that, as our group did not have an electrical engineering
 student, we would need to devote extra resources to the hardware area.
 Finally, the documentation category covered the market research and feasibility
 report, as well as the writing of the design specifications in consultation
 with software and hardware, and the keeping of minutes of all the meetings.
 
\layout Subsubsection

General Task Allocations
\layout Standard

Before the start of the project, we made an assessment of each of our abilities,
 strengths and weaknesses.
 It was immediately apparent that Stephen Kitt was best suited to software,
 while the other strong programmers were identified as Ian Clarke, Edward
 Knowelden and Duncan Irvine.
 On the hardware side, it was decided that we should have atleast one person
 who had done the CS3 Computer Design course, so James Northrop was selected.
 Stephen Cook already had some hardware experience from a school project,
 and Stuart Cox had some electrical engineering knowledge gained from Physics;
 this completed the hardware team.
 Iain Todd was put in overall charge of documentation, although it was acknowled
ged that this was not ideal.
 However, we felt that by giving each member of the group responsibility
 for documenting their own software or hardware units, we could produce
 documentation of sufficient quality and quantity.
 
\layout Standard

Having made these allocations, we then subdivided the tasks so that each
 person had a clear idea of what they were required to do.
 
\layout Subsubsection

