\layout Standard

We decided that where these task allocations were judged to be unsuitable
 or not optimal, we would either reassign the task or redefine it to make
 the work more suitable to the worker.
 However, there were few instances where this was necessary.
 Around 3 weeks into the project we decided that the audio system was a
 task that required added manpower, and so Stephen Kitt and Ian Clarke spent
 part of their time working on this, alongside Duncan.
 However, in general the task allocation proved to be effective.
\layout Subsection

Goal-setting
\layout Standard

In order to steer the group's efforts in the right direction, we set a number
 of goals during the lifetime of the project.
 At each of the supervisor meetings we gave a progress report, which helped
 to clarify the rate of progress.
 A Gantt chart was used to track this progress (see end of report).
 The Gantt chart was updated every week to reflect the state of progress
 in the project.
 This chart was made available to the supervisor as well as the other members
 of the group; however, the most effective form of feedback was definitely
 the group meetings and setting of goals.
 
\layout Subsection

Management Issues during the Project
\layout Standard

In hindsight, the group agrees that there was a slight lack of specific
 management among the software group.
 It would perhaps have been better to have a software manager in addition
 to the project manager; the existing arrangement meant that management
 attention was focused more on hardware than software.
 However, the software group was sufficiently self-motivated that this was
 not a major issue; perhaps with different people it would have been more
 of a problem.
 
\layout Standard

An early management goal was to have the hardware designed, constructed
 and tested as early as possible.
 We decided to use a considerable proportion of our consultancy budget to
 do this, and as a result the hardware was designed by the end of week 2,
 and fully constructed by the middle of week 3.
 The management focus then shifted to ensuring that the software team made
 full use of this advantage, and in particular there was a push to get the
 audio system up and running, as this was felt to have stalled somewhat.
 This involved setting specific targets for those involved, and drafting
 in extra help from others in the group, as well as using some more of our
 consultancy budget.
\layout Standard

However, by the end of the project, we had produced a prototype that did
 nearly everything it was supposed to do.
 The hardware was complete, fully tested and working, while the software
 conformed to our initial design specification, and was also substantially
 complete.
 The reasons for this achievement are varied, but undoubtedly the general
 harmony amongst the group and the consistency of attendance and effort
 of all members was a major part of this.
 
